Use conditional compilation or the `MAUI` platform-specific folders pattern. The cleanest approach:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under `Platforms/<OS>/` and is only compiled for its target (controlled by the `<ItemGroup>` conditions already in the `.csproj` template).

**Alternative** — use partial classes with a single registration:

```csharp
// Shared: Services/NotificationService.cs
public partial class NotificationService : INotificationService
{
    public partial void Show(string title, string message);
}

// Platforms/Android/NotificationService.cs
public partial class NotificationService
{
    public partial void Show(string title, string message) { /* Android impl */ }
}
```

Then register once without `#if`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, NotificationService>();
```

The partial-class approach is generally preferred — it avoids preprocessor directives in `MauiProgram.cs` and lets the build system handle platform targeting automatically.
